results.notes:
When I first saw these I thought, “Look at those Entoloma mushrooms growing on wood.” An examination of the gill attachment was not very helpful, as the area where they approach/meet the stipe was somewhat damaged and beginning to decay. I took the one fruit body for study. The oldest one was fairly decayed and the button (photos labeled using the letter “B”) was probably not mature enough to drop spores. I later scoped the spores and to my my surprise, they were not angular. Looked like Pluteus spores. I had run across some P. cervinus a short time after seeing these mushrooms. So, I wondered if I had mistakenly scoped the wrong material. I returned to the site the next day (5/30) and found the one young fruit body had matured. I took this home and scoped some gill. It’s a Pluteus!
Gills deeply adnexed near the stipe.
Spores broadly ellipsoid to subglobose, 6.5-8 × 5-6.5 (larger from the initial spore drop).
Cheilocystidia abundant and forming a three-tiered palisade; septate at the tapered end and smoothly variously-shaped apices some capped/encrusted.
Pleurocystidia scattered, elaborately ornamented (see last two photos).

Macro: thallus composed of brown, gray-rimmed squamules and black lecideine-looking apothecia with gray rims that become excluded with age. Young apothecia have algae in margins visible in section. Micro: hypothecium hyaline, epihymenium dark brown with olive green tints. Hymenium incl. epi ~50 micrometers tall. Younger aps with algae in margin (lecanorine). Cortex ~25 micrometers thick, epinecral layer ~9 micrometers thick.

Chemistry: medulla I- (turning reddish, not blue), hymenium I+ blue. Asci with I+ dark blue tholus. Thallus and apothecia K-, C-, KC-.

results.notes:
Growing gregariously on the underside of a decorticated Pinus taeda log in a mixed pine-hardwood forest. Basidiocarps pure white; pendent; finely hairy; tubular; up to 1 mm long and 0.4 mm wide. Subiculum absent. All structures hyaline. Clamps present on tramal hyphae. All structures inamyloid. Hairs sparsely branched; smooth. Basidia 2-sterigmate, at least some basally clamped. Branched hairs occurring over the entire exterior of basidiocarps and not just the on the “mouth” of the tube. Spores hyaline, smooth, thin-walled and subglobose.
